About Figure 1

Several Observations have newcasedensity > 0.05. They are not shown in the Figure 1 to improve informativity.

The fitted smooth line is a U-shaped curve. Therefore we add a quadratic term of seconddose to detect whether the U-shaped relationship is significant.

Explanation

Our regression models indicate that with the growing second dose vaccination completion ratio and third dose vaccination completion ratio, the new case density, which is (new cases) / (population), drops at the beginning, but rises up after reaching to a high level of the vaccination ratio (61.6% for second-dose, 34.3% for third-dose). All coefficients are significant at 1% level.

Such a trend can be explained through population density ratio, policy changes, and weaker policy implementation. Since our regressions are at the county level, there are many counties with a low population density ratio. In these counties, social distance can be naturally and more easily achieved in public area, thus a lower new case density. Futhermore, counties with high vaccination ratios tend to loose the covid safety restrctions, which leads a higher new case density. Similarly, residents in these counties also care relatively less if they strictly obligate the safety restrictions, and expose themselves to a higher infection risk.

Thankfully, recent variations of coronavirus are not likely to cause severe symtoms and death, so a sligtly higher new case density wont be a serious problem.
